[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1179},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2022\u002F11\u002F15\u002Fprettier-git-commit-with-git-cz\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2022\u002F11\u002F15\u002Fprettier-git-commit-with-git-cz\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2022\u002F11\u002F15\u002Fprettier-git-commit-with-git-cz\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2022\u002F11\u002F15\u002Fprettier-git-commit-with-git-cz\u002F":1156,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2022\u002F11\u002F15\u002Fprettier-git-commit-with-git-cz\u002F":1165},"\u002Fgit\u002F20221115\u002F721294310\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1139,"date":1140,"description":1141,"extension":1142,"lang":1143,"meta":1144,"navigation":1145,"path":1146,"readingMinutes":1147,"seo":1148,"standalone":1149,"stem":1150,"tags":1151,"tldr":1153,"updated":1140,"url":1154,"__hash__":1155},"content\u002Fen\u002FGit\u002Fprettier-git-commit-with-git-cz.md","Prettier Git Commits With git-cz","9430721294",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1127},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,33,36,61,64,71,74,77,80,88,94,102,105,110,113,142,145,149,156,169,172,194,205,210,213,219,226,231,238,243,250,256,263,266,277,280,288,291,295,298,305,1026,1029,1035,1039,1042,1048,1058,1067,1070,1074,1083,1099,1105,1112,1116,1123],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Ever thought your Git commits look kind of ugly? Or you sit there wondering what to even write? If so, this post introduces git-cz — a tool that frees you from writing commit messages by hand and makes them prettier. Lazy developer's paradise — not even an exaggeration.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"why-git-commit-messages-matter","Why Git commit messages matter",[17,25,26,27,32],{},"Let's start by talking about why Git commit messages matter. I wrote about this before in ",[28,29,31],"a",{"href":30},"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F14\u002Fgit-flow-and-commit-conventions\u002F","Git Flow and Commit Conventions",", and one section in there is about Commit Types.",[17,34,35],{},"The Commit Type basically signals what kind of change this commit is:",[37,38,39,43,46,49,52,55,58],"ul",{},[40,41,42],"li",{},"feat - new feature or feature change",[40,44,45],{},"fix - bug fix",[40,47,48],{},"docs - documentation",[40,50,51],{},"style - formatting\u002Fstyle changes that don't affect logic (ESLint, missing semicolons...)",[40,53,54],{},"refactor - refactoring\u002Foptimization, not a bug or new feature",[40,56,57],{},"test - adding missing tests",[40,59,60],{},"chore - third-party tooling, maintenance, etc.",[17,62,63],{},"Even knowing this, in real dev work you often forget what each Commit Type means or aren't sure which one fits — so you end up with ugly commit messages like...",[17,65,66],{},[67,68],"img",{"alt":69,"src":70},"A pile of meaningless commits","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FmvvoGyr.png",[17,72,73],{},"That's from my own blog. A bunch of meaningless commits. Why? Because my lazy gene kicked in and I didn't want to think about which Commit Type to use.",[17,75,76],{},"To solve this, let me introduce the tool of the day — git-cz.",[12,78,79],{"id":79},"git-cz",[17,81,82,87],{},[28,83,79],{"href":84,"rel":85},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fstreamich\u002Fgit-cz",[86],"nofollow"," is a commit manager that unifies your commit format and makes them prettier. For example:",[17,89,90],{},[67,91],{"alt":92,"src":93},"Image","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FVoqohiU.png",[17,95,96,97,101],{},"That's me demoing git-cz. Way better than a raw ",[98,99,100],"code",{},"post",", with cute emoji included. That commit message — kind of nice, right?",[17,103,104],{},"How do you use it? git-cz has multiple install methods (npm or npx). I'll use npm and install it globally — chances are you'll fall in love with it and want it in other projects too, so global save you from installing it per project.",[106,107,109],"h3",{"id":108},"install-git-cz","Install git-cz",[17,111,112],{},"Open your terminal and run:",[114,115,120],"pre",{"className":116,"code":117,"language":118,"meta":119,"style":119},"language-bash shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","npm install -g git-cz\n","bash","",[98,121,122],{"__ignoreMap":119},[123,124,127,131,135,139],"span",{"class":125,"line":126},"line",1,[123,128,130],{"class":129},"s_sBn","npm",[123,132,134],{"class":133},"sTRMh"," install",[123,136,138],{"class":137},"sCcAr"," -g",[123,140,141],{"class":133}," git-cz\n",[17,143,144],{},"That's it — really. Now we can start using git-cz.",[106,146,148],{"id":147},"using-git-cz","Using git-cz",[17,150,151,152,155],{},"Open any project, ",[98,153,154],{},"cd"," into the project folder, and run:",[114,157,159],{"className":116,"code":158,"language":118,"meta":119,"style":119},"git cz\n",[98,160,161],{"__ignoreMap":119},[123,162,163,166],{"class":125,"line":126},[123,164,165],{"class":129},"git",[123,167,168],{"class":133}," cz\n",[17,170,171],{},"You'll probably get this error:",[114,173,175],{"className":116,"code":174,"language":118,"meta":119,"style":119},"✖  error     No files staged!\n",[98,176,177],{"__ignoreMap":119},[123,178,179,182,185,188,191],{"class":125,"line":126},[123,180,181],{"class":129},"✖",[123,183,184],{"class":133},"  error",[123,186,187],{"class":133},"     No",[123,189,190],{"class":133}," files",[123,192,193],{"class":133}," staged!\n",[17,195,196,197,200,201,204],{},"That's because you haven't staged any files (",[98,198,199],{},"git add .","). So stage your files first, then run ",[98,202,203],{},"git cz"," again — now you'll see git-cz's UI.",[17,206,207],{},[67,208],{"alt":79,"src":209},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002F0nv9riK.png",[17,211,212],{},"Use arrow keys to pick your commit type. These are git-cz's defaults (I'll cover customization later). Select one and press Enter — git-cz will then ask you to fill in the commit description.",[17,214,215],{},[67,216],{"alt":217,"src":218},"Enter commit message","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fn6hpyff.png",[17,220,221,222,225],{},"After typing the description, hit Enter again and it asks: ",[98,223,224],{},"Provide a longer description of the change",". This is for a more detailed description. If you don't need one, just hit Enter to skip.",[17,227,228],{},[67,229],{"alt":224,"src":230},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FVumvDYy.png",[17,232,233,234,237],{},"Next: ",[98,235,236],{},"List any breaking changes",". If there aren't any, hit Enter to skip.",[17,239,240],{},[67,241],{"alt":236,"src":242},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FJieVcKJ.png",[17,244,245,246,249],{},"Last one: ",[98,247,248],{},"Issues this commit closes, e.g #123",". If there's no related issue, Enter to skip. And your commit is done.",[17,251,252],{},[67,253],{"alt":254,"src":255},"Commit done","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FsZJXrlo.png",[17,257,258,259,262],{},"Through this select-and-answer flow, you get a nice clean commit message effortlessly. The conventions are basically the same as my ",[28,260,261],{"href":30},"Git Commit Conventions"," post, so you can keep using the same mental model — but commit faster, with no format slips or typos. Genuine brain-saver.",[17,264,265],{},"One reminder — once you switch to git-cz, you need to adjust your command flow slightly:",[17,267,268,270,271,270,274],{},[98,269,199],{}," => ",[98,272,273],{},"git commit -m 'first'",[98,275,276],{},"git push",[17,278,279],{},"Becomes:",[17,281,282,270,284,270,286],{},[98,283,199],{},[98,285,203],{},[98,287,276],{},[17,289,290],{},"That's how you use git-cz correctly.",[106,292,294],{"id":293},"customizing-git-cz","Customizing git-cz",[17,296,297],{},"If git-cz's default commit types aren't enough, you can customize them.",[17,299,300,301,304],{},"Open your project, create a file called ",[98,302,303],{},"changelog.config.js"," in the project root. Here's the default config from the official docs, with my added Chinese comments (you can ignore those):",[114,306,310],{"className":307,"code":308,"language":309,"meta":119,"style":119},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","module.exports = {\n  disableEmoji: false, \u002F\u002F whether to disable emoji\n  format: '{type}{scope}: {emoji}{subject}', \u002F\u002F commit message format\n  list: ['test', 'feat', 'fix', 'chore', 'docs', 'refactor', 'style', 'ci', 'perf'], \u002F\u002F commit type list\n  maxMessageLength: 64, \u002F\u002F max commit message length\n  minMessageLength: 3, \u002F\u002F min commit message length\n  questions: ['type', 'scope', 'subject', 'body', 'breaking', 'issues', 'lerna'], \u002F\u002F list of questions\n  scopes: [], \u002F\u002F commit scope list\n  types: { \u002F\u002F commit type definitions\n    chore: {\n      description: 'Build process or auxiliary tool changes',\n      emoji: '🤖',\n      value: 'chore'\n    },\n    ci: {\n      description: 'CI related changes',\n      emoji: '🎡',\n      value: 'ci'\n    },\n    docs: {\n      description: 'Documentation only changes',\n      emoji: '✏️',\n      value: 'docs'\n    },\n    feat: {\n      description: 'A new feature',\n      emoji: '🎸',\n      value: 'feat'\n    },\n    fix: {\n      description: 'A bug fix',\n      emoji: '🐛',\n      value: 'fix'\n    },\n    perf: {\n      description: 'A code change that improves performance',\n      emoji: '⚡️',\n      value: 'perf'\n    },\n    refactor: {\n      description: 'A code change that neither fixes a bug or adds a feature',\n      emoji: '💡',\n      value: 'refactor'\n    },\n    release: {\n      description: 'Create a release commit',\n      emoji: '🏹',\n      value: 'release'\n    },\n    style: {\n      description: 'Markup, white-space, formatting, missing semi-colons...',\n      emoji: '💄',\n      value: 'style'\n    },\n    test: {\n      description: 'Adding missing tests',\n      emoji: '💍',\n      value: 'test'\n    },\n  },\n  messages: {\n    type: 'Select the type of change that you\\'re committing:',\n    customScope: 'Select the scope this component affects:',\n    subject: 'Write a short, imperative mood description of the change:\\n',\n    body: 'Provide a longer description of the change:\\n ',\n    breaking: 'List any breaking changes:\\n',\n    footer: 'Issues this commit closes, e.g #123:',\n    confirmCommit: 'The packages that this commit has affected\\n',\n  },\n};\n","js",[98,311,312,331,347,361,416,430,444,488,497,506,512,524,535,544,550,556,566,576,584,589,595,605,615,623,628,634,644,654,662,667,673,683,693,701,706,712,722,732,740,745,751,761,771,779,784,790,800,810,818,823,829,839,849,857,862,868,878,888,896,901,907,913,930,941,958,974,989,1000,1015,1020],{"__ignoreMap":119},[123,313,314,317,321,324,328],{"class":125,"line":126},[123,315,316],{"class":137},"module",[123,318,320],{"class":319},"sMAXC",".",[123,322,323],{"class":137},"exports",[123,325,327],{"class":326},"sWyjQ"," =",[123,329,330],{"class":319}," {\n",[123,332,334,337,340,343],{"class":125,"line":333},2,[123,335,336],{"class":319},"  disableEmoji: ",[123,338,339],{"class":137},"false",[123,341,342],{"class":319},", ",[123,344,346],{"class":345},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F whether to disable emoji\n",[123,348,350,353,356,358],{"class":125,"line":349},3,[123,351,352],{"class":319},"  format: ",[123,354,355],{"class":133},"'{type}{scope}: {emoji}{subject}'",[123,357,342],{"class":319},[123,359,360],{"class":345},"\u002F\u002F commit message format\n",[123,362,364,367,370,372,375,377,380,382,385,387,390,392,395,397,400,402,405,407,410,413],{"class":125,"line":363},4,[123,365,366],{"class":319},"  list: [",[123,368,369],{"class":133},"'test'",[123,371,342],{"class":319},[123,373,374],{"class":133},"'feat'",[123,376,342],{"class":319},[123,378,379],{"class":133},"'fix'",[123,381,342],{"class":319},[123,383,384],{"class":133},"'chore'",[123,386,342],{"class":319},[123,388,389],{"class":133},"'docs'",[123,391,342],{"class":319},[123,393,394],{"class":133},"'refactor'",[123,396,342],{"class":319},[123,398,399],{"class":133},"'sty